We aim at aligning the language model to the trustworthy status where it supplies responses in accordance with merely the retrieved evidence and ignores the parametric knowledge. To achieve this goal, we propose a simple yet effective reinforcement learning (RL) algorithm which rewards the model's reliance on contextual knowledge and penalizes its reliance on parametric knowledge. Specifically, given the question \(q\) and substituted context \(c^{s}\), we reward \(\pi_{	heta}\) as long as the counterfactual answer \(y^{s}\) appears in the terminated response and penalize it if the original answer \(y^{o}\) appears or neither answers are included, formulated as \[r_{t}^{	ext{trust}}= egin{cases}+\alpha_{0}&	ext{if }s_{t+1}	ext{ ends }\wedge y^{s}\subseteq s_{t+1}\wedge y^{o}
subseteq s_{t+1}\ -\alpha_{1}&	ext{if }s_{t+1}	ext{ ends }\wedge y^{s}
subseteq s_{t+1}\wedge y^{o} 
subseteq s_{t+1}\ -\alpha_{0}&	ext{if }s_{t+1}	ext{ ends }\wedge y^{o}\subseteq s_{t+1}\ 0&	ext{otherwise}\end{cases}, 	ag{5}\] where \(\alpha_{0}\) and \(\alpha_{1}\) control absolute values of reward and penalty. Note that only the last generated token is rewarded so that this reward is on the sentence level. Indispensably, a Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence term is added to the reward following preceding works (Jaques et al., 2019; Stiennon et al., 2020) to penalize the policy's deviation from the original supervised fine-tuned model \(\pi^{	ext{SFT}}\), formulated as \[r_{t}^{	ext{KL}}=-\alpha_{2}\log\left[ rac{\pi_{	heta}(a_{t}|s_{t})}{\pi^{ 	ext{SFT}}(a_{t}|s_{t})}ight], 	ag{6}\] where \(\alpha_{2}\) is a coefficient controlling the training trade-off between a model performing specific task and a model more like the original one. Even with the regularization of KL divergence, LLMs are prone to falling into local optima in the training procedure of RL. For instance, pre-trained LLM may continually output the same repeated pattern when a short repetitive string like "\( ackslash\)n\( ackslash\)n\( ackslash\)n" shows up in the prompt, which will be reinforced and overwhelm the cumulative \(r_{t}^{	ext{trust}}\) in the subsequent training procedure by virtue of its low accumulative KL penalty. To avoid this, we propose an additional collapse penalty to persuade the LLM from collapsed mode: \[r_{t}^{	ext{col}}=g(s_{t+1})= egin{cases}-\alpha_{3}&	ext{if }s_{t+1}	ext{ ends and collapses}\ 0&	ext{otherwise}\end{cases}, 	ag{7}\] where \(\alpha_{3}\) controls the absolute value of \(r_{t}^{	ext{col}}\) and the collapse detection algorithm is described in Appendix C. Overall, the final reward function is formulated as \[r(s_{t},a_{t})=r_{t}^{	ext{trust}}+r_{t}^{	ext{col}}+r_{t}^{	ext{KL}}. 	ag{8}\] We train the policy with PPO algorithm (Schulman et al., 2017). We propose an annealing strategy to trade-off between exploration and exploitation in PPO training of LLMs, which is detailed in Appendix B due to space constraints. The algorithm pipeline of Trustworthy-Alignment is described in Appendix C.
